In Magns's first world championship challenger match against Vishy, it was Magnus who was the favourite not Vishy. Most people predicted that Magnus would win it and continue to dominate for  the next 10 or so years. Although Vishy was known to play better in the World championship than what his rating suggests, you still can't ignore the fact that Magnus was the highest rated player by a big margin and was rated almost a 100 points above VIshy. 
Although the documentary was very well made, I can't help but criticise that it failed to mention the sheer significance of rating difference between Carlsen and Karjakin when they played and also that Magnus was considered the clear favourite going into it. Not showing the difference might make it seem more dramatic and tense which might be better for captivating new audiences, it reduces the surprise when Karjakin took the lead since Carlsen was supposed to win comfortably.
Overall I don't get why people don't wish to have a single dominant champion like Magnus. Although no one else might have a realistic chance of winning the world championship, I don't get why people prefer the results having more luck and randomness. Ideally I would like there to be as little luck as possible so that the person who is stronger wins. Having too much instability and having people who are weaker win due to luck just leaves a bad taste about the tournament or title.

Carlsen's overall dominance - that led him to this position in the first place - was very impressive, but the sacrifice in and of itself was just a cherry on the top. Live commenters saw it instantly at that point. It would be a fairly easy chess puzzle.
So it's hard to agree with the Fischer analogy, where the game was far from over after the sacrifice.
